Ideally located in the Hunza valley, Hunza Embassy Hotel rooms are comfortable rooms (double or single with a fan , and an attached bathroom ( hot water is always available.

Most rooms have a lovely terrace from where you can have a look at the Hunza valley and the dramatic scenery around. Behind the hotel you will see 7,000m high mountains on a clear day (even in July, chances are high that you will be able to see the peaks). Ask for the higher rooms as the view is much more dramatic. 

Good prices food and rooms ,there is a communal dinner with the travellers staying overnight: that night,noodles soup and vegetables rice. hunza traditional food and many kind of food always available. 

The hostel can also arrange treks for you if you plan to stay several days, and keep your luggage in a cloakroom while you are away.

It is a short walk (10 minutes) from Karimabad village centre and 20 minutes from Baltit Fort. 

Ideally located in the Hunza valley, Hunza Embassy Hotel rooms are comfortable rooms (double or single with a fan , and an attached bathroom ( hot water is always available.

Most rooms have a lovely terrace from where you can have a look at the Hunza valley and the dramatic scenery around. Behind the hotel you will see 7,000m high mountains on a clear day (even in July, chances are high that you will be able to see the peaks). Ask for the higher rooms as the view is much more dramatic. 

Good prices food and rooms ,there is a communal dinner with the travellers staying overnight: that night,noodles soup and vegetables rice. hunza traditional food and many kind of food always available. 

The hostel can also arrange treks for you if you plan to stay several days, and keep your luggage in a cloakroom while you are away.

a nice traditional restaurant for meat lover. Most of the dishes are Pakistani & Afghani style BBQ / roast meat. 
Most of the sitting arrangement in the restuarant is of traditional Balochi style, ie, on the carpet with large size cushions. You sit on the carpet (on floor) leaning on the traditional cushions. However, formal table and chair sitting is also available. Most locals like to sit on the carpet as it goes along with the local tradition. 
We ordered BBQ mutton chops, BBQ mutton boti and white mutton karahi along with Afghani naan. The local karahi is quite oily and we knew it, however, we were astonished to see oil dripping from our BBQ chops. They were no doubt barbecued on coal but were perhaps dipped in oil or something later, ruining the meat texture. BBQ mutton boti was better and we enjoyed it. 
Overall a tasty food but too oily. 
Rates are quite reasonable and it will cost you 600-900 per head. Enough parking space is The quality of naan (local bread) is simply outstanding. At the end of the meal, as it is usual with Pakistani / Afghani restaurants in Quetta, a green tea / qahwa is a must. Perched on the hillside with awesome views they guys are serving up Nespresso coffee. The food is nice with European style items like pancakes & rosti. 
The coffee is great but I was very impressed with the pink Kashmiri tea, such an explosion of flavours. In the high season make sure to book a table the day before as it can get super busy. 

You can also buy quality organic honey & apricot oil from there small selection of local products. As you walk up the wooden steps, you will find a friendly staff awaiting to take your orders. The Cafe offers magnificent views of Rakaposhi peak, especially when the sun is going down. The menu offers a range of mouth-watering treats. We ordered Walnut cake slices, Hunza herbal green tea (tumoro - wild thyme tea) and Kashmiri tea, served with delicious honey. The cake has a crispy crust topped with a heavy filling of walnuts caramelized with honey. Apart from that we ordered chocolate brownie and coffee. All the products were fresh and the dishes had the warmth of home-made food. The chefs takes great care in selecting the best quality ingredients. Since last 4 years we have had a pleasant dining experience with food of the most exquisite flavours. People come, talk to the enterprising lady who runs the kitchen, find a place to fit themselves in, on the couches, place an order and relax. 
We were a family of 9 and could not fit in the small room, so sat next to the road outside watching a local wedding take place when the kids shouted out that the small courtyard under a big shady tree is now empty so that is where we all ran and grabbed the only two tables.
